{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778981346414,"sessionID":"ses_1cc731d29ffeAv83jd6twnaLta","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_QSDIwqApDPQ8zHmZBzLcXfJQ","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-uberon/eval-ont-agent-uberon/__issue_context__.json","offset":1,"limit":400},"output":"<path>/__w/eval-ont-agent-uberon/eval-ont-agent-uberon/__issue_context__.json</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: {\n2:   \"body\": \"PR #3374 introduced the two following `disjoint_from` tags:\\n\\n```\\n[Term]\\nid: UBERON:0000001\\ndisjoint_from: GO:0005623 ! cell\\ndisjoint_from: GO:0110165 ! cellular anatomical entity\\n```\\n\\nNothing wrong with that addition _per se_, except that, whenever the edit file is written back by any OWLAPI-based application (e.g. Protégé or ROBOT), those tags will become:\\n\\n```\\n[Term]\\nid: GO:0005623\\ndisjoint_from: UBERON:0000001\\n\\n[Term]\\nid: GO:0110165\\ndisjoint_from: UBERON:0000001\\n```\\n\\nSemantically, from a OWL point of view, this does not change anything: both forms represent the following disjointness axioms:\\n\\n```\\nDisjointClasses(GO:0005623 UBERON:0000001)\\nDisjointClasses(GO:0110165 UBERON:0000001)\\n```\\n\\nbecause the order of the operands of a _DisjointClasses_ axiom is not significant. And since it is not significant, there is no way for the OBO serializer to know that it should attach the corresponding tags to the `UBERON:0000001` term frame, rather than creating new term frames for `GO:0005623` and `GO:0110165` – when it has to translate `DisjointClasses(GO:0005623 UBERON:0000001)` into OBO, the OBO serializer simply adds the tag to the frame for the operand that comes first in lexicographical order (so in this case, `GO:0005623` rather than `UBERON:0000001`, since _G < U_).\\n\\nBut from a OBO point of view, the two forms are _not_ equivalent, because in the second form we now have two new term frames that do not have a label. And missing labels is an **error**.\\n\\nPossible solutions:\\n\\n(A) Finally admit that the OBO format is not worth the trouble, and switch the edit file to OWL Functional Syntax. I am mentioning that for completeness, I know there is no hope of that happening in my lifetime.\\n\\n(B) Move the disjointness axioms to an separate component in OWL Functional Syntax.\\n\\n(C) Add labels to the disjoint GO terms.\\n\\nSince (A) will never happen, the second best solution is (B) in my opinion.\",\n3:   \"comments\": [\n4:     {\n5:       \"id\": \"IC_kwDOAAidd87gubj5\",\n6:       \"author\": {\n7:         \"login\": \"cmungall\"\n8:       },\n9:       \"authorAssociation\": \"MEMBER\",\n10:       \"body\": \"Good catch!\\r\\n\\r\\nYes, we should move to a component. We have disjoint_union_over.owl which\\r\\nis terminologically a poor choice but functionally it fits the bill.\\r\\n\\r\\nRegarding (A), I predict we will see a move to yaml as source for\\r\\nforward-thinking ontologies this year, and bypass these restrictive legacy\\r\\nformats forever, except for exporting.\\r\\n\\r\\nOn Mon, Jan 19, 2026 at 2:00 PM Damien Goutte-Gattat <\\r\\n***@***.***> wrote:\\r\\n\\r\\n> *gouttegd* created an issue (obophenotype/uberon#3651)\\r\\n> <https://github.com/obophenotype/uberon/issues/3651>\\r\\n>\\r\\n> PR #3374 <https://github.com/obophenotype/uberon/pull/3374> introduced\\r\\n> the two following disjoint_from tags:\\r\\n>\\r\\n> [Term]\\r\\n> id: UBERON:0000001\\r\\n> disjoint_from: GO:0005623 ! cell\\r\\n> disjoint_from: GO:0110165 ! cellular anatomical entity\\r\\n>\\r\\n> Nothing wrong with that addition *per se*, except that, whenever the edit\\r\\n> file is written back by any OWLAPI-based application (e.g. Protégé or\\r\\n> ROBOT), those tags will become:\\r\\n>\\r\\n> [Term]\\r\\n> id: GO:0005623\\r\\n> disjoint_from: UBERON:0000001\\r\\n>\\r\\n> [Term]\\r\\n> id: GO:0110165\\r\\n> disjoint_from: UBERON:0000001\\r\\n>\\r\\n> Semantically, from a OWL point of view, this does not change anything:\\r\\n> both form represents the following disjointness axioms:\\r\\n>\\r\\n> DisjointClasses(GO:0005623 UBERON:0000001)\\r\\n> DisjointClasses(GO:0110165 UBERON:0000001)\\r\\n>\\r\\n> because the order of the operands of a *DisjointClasses* axiom is not\\r\\n> significant. And since it is not significant, there is no way for the OBO\\r\\n> serializer to know that it should attach the corresponding tags to the\\r\\n> UBERON:0000001 term frame, rather than creating new term frames for\\r\\n> GO:0005623 and GO:0110165 – when it has to translate DisjointClasses(GO:0005623\\r\\n> UBERON:0000001) into OBO, the OBO serializer simply adds the tag to the\\r\\n> frame for the operand that comes first in lexicographical order (so in this\\r\\n> case, GO:0005623 r... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n11:       \"createdAt\": \"2026-01-19T22:07:03Z\",\n12:       \"includesCreatedEdit\": false,\n13:       \"isMinimized\": false,\n14:       \"minimizedReason\": \"\",\n15:       \"reactionGroups\": [],\n16:       \"url\": \"https://github.com/obophenotype/uberon/issues/3651#issuecomment-3770267897\",\n17:       \"viewerDidAuthor\": true\n18:     }\n19:   ],\n20:   \"title\": \"Newly introduced disjointness axioms cause OBO serialisation issue\",\n21:   \"url\": \"https://github.com/obophenotype/uberon/issues/3651\"\n22: }\n\n(End of file - total 22 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"{\n  \"body\": \"PR #3374 introduced the two following `disjoint_from` tags:\\n\\n```\\n[Term]\\nid: UBERON:0000001\\ndisjoint_from: GO:0005623 ! cell\\ndisjoint_from: GO:0110165 ! cellular anatomical entity\\n```\\n\\nNothing wrong with that addition _per se_, except that, whenever the edit file is written back by any OWLAPI-based application (e.g. Protégé or ROBOT), those tags will become:\\n\\n```\\n[Term]\\nid: GO:0005623\\ndisjoint_from: UBERON:0000001\\n\\n[Term]\\nid: GO:0110165\\ndisjoint_from: UBERON:0000001\\n```\\n\\nSemantically, from a OWL point of view, this does not change anything: both forms represent the following disjointness axioms:\\n\\n```\\nDisjointClasses(GO:0005623 UBERON:0000001)\\nDisjointClasses(GO:0110165 UBERON:0000001)\\n```\\n\\nbecause the order of the operands of a _DisjointClasses_ axiom is not significant. And since it is not significant, there is no way for the OBO serializer to know that it should attach the corresponding tags to the `UBERON:0000001` term frame, rather than creating new term frames for `GO:0005623` and `GO:0110165` – when it has to translate `DisjointClasses(GO:0005623 UBERON:0000001)` into OBO, the OBO serializer simply adds the tag to the frame for the operand that comes first in lexicographical order (so in this case, `GO:0005623` rather than `UBERON:0000001`, since _G < U_).\\n\\nBut from a OBO point of view, the two forms are _not_ equivalent, because in the second form we now have two new term frames that do not have a label. And missing labels is an **error**.\\n\\nPossible solutions:\\n\\n(A) Finally admit that the OBO format is not worth the trouble, and switch the edit file to OWL Functional Syntax. I am mentioning that for completeness, I know there is no hope of that happening in my lifetime.\\n\\n(B) Move the disjointness axioms to an separate component in OWL Functional Syntax.\\n\\n(C) Add labels to the disjoint GO terms.\\n\\nSince (A) will never happen, the second best solution is (B) in my opinion.\",\n  \"comments\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"IC_kwDOAAidd87gubj5\",\n      \"author\": {\n        \"login\": \"cmungall\"\n      },\n      \"authorAssociation\": \"MEMBER\",\n      \"body\": \"Good catch!\\r\\n\\r\\nYes, we should move to a component. We have disjoint_union_over.owl which\\r\\nis terminologically a poor choice but functionally it fits the bill.\\r\\n\\r\\nRegarding (A), I predict we will see a move to yaml as source for\\r\\nforward-thinking ontologies this year, and bypass these restrictive legacy\\r\\nformats forever, except for exporting.\\r\\n\\r\\nOn Mon, Jan 19, 2026 at 2:00 PM Damien Goutte-Gattat <\\r\\n***@***.***> wrote:\\r\\n\\r\\n> *gouttegd* created an issue (obophenotype/uberon#3651)\\r\\n> <https://github.com/obophenotype/uberon/issues/3651>\\r\\n>\\r\\n> PR #3374 <https://github.com/obophenotype/uberon/pull/3374> introduced\\r\\n> the two following disjoint_from tags:\\r\\n>\\r\\n> [Term]\\r\\n> id: UBERON:0000001\\r\\n> disjoint_from: GO:0005623 ! cell\\r\\n> disjoint_from: GO:0110165 ! cellular anatomical entity\\r\\n>\\r\\n> Nothing wrong with that addition *per se*, except that, whenever the edit\\r\\n> file is written back by any OWLAPI-based application (e.g. Protégé or\\r\\n> ROBOT), those tags will become:\\r\\n>\\r\\n> [Term]\\r\\n> id: GO:0005623\\r\\n> disjoint_from: UBERON:0000001\\r\\n>\\r\\n> [Term]\\r\\n> id: GO:0110165\\r\\n> disjoint_from: UBERON:0000001\\r\\n>\\r\\n> Semantically, from a OWL point of view, this does not change anything:\\r\\n> both form represents the following disjointness axioms:\\r\\n>\\r\\n> DisjointClasses(GO:0005623 UBERON:0000001)\\r\\n> DisjointClasses(GO:0110165 UBERON:0000001)\\r\\n>\\r\\n> because the order of the operands of a *DisjointClasses* axiom is not\\r\\n> significant. And since it is not significant, there is no way for the OBO\\r\\n> serializer to know that it should attach the corresponding tags to the\\r\\n> UBERON:0000001 term frame, rather than creating new term frames for\\r\\n> GO:0005623 and GO:0110165 – when it has to translate DisjointClasses(GO:0005623\\r\\n> UBERON:0000001) into OBO, the OBO serializer simply adds the tag to the\\r\\n> frame for the operand that comes first in lexicographical order (so in this\\r\\n> case, GO:0005623 r... (line truncated to 2000 chars)\n      \"createdAt\": \"2026-01-19T22:07:03Z\",\n      \"includesCreatedEdit\": false,\n      \"isMinimized\": false,\n      \"minimizedReason\": \"\",\n      \"reactionGroups\": [],\n      \"url\": \"https://github.com/obophenotype/uberon/issues/3651#issuecomment-3770267897\",\n      \"viewerDidAuthor\": true\n    }\n  ],\n  \"title\": \"Newly introduced disjointness axioms cause OBO serialisation issue\",","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"__issue_context__.json","time":{"start":1778981346380,"end":1778981346411}},"id":"prt_e338d1c44001QZwiPGy3sstLzH","sessionID":"ses_1cc731d29ffeAv83jd6twnaLta","messageID":"msg_e338d0eb5001kgiFoFIdvqc5oa"}}
{"type":"tool_use","timestamp":1778981346435,"sessionID":"ses_1cc731d29ffeAv83jd6twnaLta","part":{"type":"tool","tool":"read","callID":"call_cWZONmjQZUhxl6MUxEATVoM0","state":{"status":"completed","input":{"filePath":"/__w/eval-ont-agent-uberon/eval-ont-agent-uberon/AGENTS.md","offset":1,"limit":260},"output":"<path>/__w/eval-ont-agent-uberon/eval-ont-agent-uberon/AGENTS.md</path>\n<type>file</type>\n<content>\n1: # UBERON Ontology Project Guide\n2: \n3: This includes instructions for editing the uberon ontology. \n4: \n5: ## Project Layout\n6: - Main development file is `src/ontology/uberon-edit.obo`\n7: - individual terms checked out in `terms`\n8: - ODK and ontology documentation can be found in `/docs/`\n9: \n10: ## Querying ontology\n11: \n12: - To look at a specific term if you know the ID:\n13:     - `obo-grep.pl -r 'id: UBERON:0004177' src/ontology/uberon-edit.obo`\n14: - All mentions of an ID\n15:     - `obo-grep.pl -r 'UBERON:0004177' src/ontology/uberon-edit.obo`\n16: - Note that `obo-grep.pl` is in your PATH, no need to search for it    \n17: - Only search over `src/ontology/uberon-edit.obo`\n18: - DO NOT bother doing your own greps over the file, or looking for other files, unless otherwise asked, you will just waste time.\n19: - ONLY use the methods above for searching the ontology\n20: \n21: ## Before making edits\n22: - Read the request carefully and make a plan, especially if there is nuance\n23: - If related issues are mentioned read them: `gh issue view GITHUB-ISSUE-NUMBER`\n24: - if a PMID is mentioned in the issue, ALWAYS try and read it\n25: - ALWAYS check proposed parent terms for consistency\n26: - For terms that are compositional, check `src/patterns/dosdp-patterns/*.yaml`\n27: \n28: ## Editors guide\n29: - design patterns are in docs/patterns\n30: \n31: ## Edits\n32: - IMPORTANT: Do not edit the edit file directly, it's large\n33: - Add edits should be made in the `terms/` folder\n34: - check out a term into `terms/`: `obo-checkout.pl src/ontology/uberon-edit.obo UBERON:1234567 [OTHER IDS]`\n35: - This will create a single stanza obo files `terms/UBERON_1234567.obo` which you can easily edit\n36:      - (note the colon is replaced with an underscore)\n37: - You can go ahead and edit the smallers files in the `terms/` folder\n38: - After edits, check back in: `obo-checkin.pl src/ontology/uberon-edit.obo UBERON:1234567 [OTHER IDS]`\n39: - if you like you can edit multiple terms in one batch, e.g. `terms/my_batch.obo`\n40:      - `obo-checkout.pl src/ontology/uberon-edit.obo terms/my_batch.obo`\n41: - checking in will update the edit file and remove the file from `terms/`\n42: - before committing, src/ontology/uberon-edit.obo should be reserialised via `robot convert -i  src/ontology/uberon-edit.obo -f obo -o src/ontology/uberon-edit.obo`\n43: - Commits are then made on src/ontology/uberon-edit.obo as appropriate\n44: - Note that `obo-checkin.pl` and `obo-checkout.pl` are in your PATH, no need to search for it\n45: - New terms must have:\n46:    - `relationship: dc-contributor https://orcid.org/<ORCID> ! <NAME>`, where this is the person(s) in the issue\n47:    - `property_value: dcterms-date \"<ISO-TIMESTAMP>\" xsd:dateTime`\n48: \n49: \n50: \n51: ## OBO Format Guidelines\n52: - Term ID format: UBERON:NNNNNNN (7-digit number)\n53: - Handling New Term Requests (NTRs):\n54:   - New terms start  UBERON:99xxxxx\n55: - Each term requires: id, name, definition with references\n56: - Never guess UBERON IDs, or ontology term IDs, use search tools above to determine actual term\n57: - Never guess PMIDs for references, do a web search if needed\n58: - Use standard relationship types: is_a, part_of, has_part, etc.\n59: - Follow existing term patterns for consistency\n60: \n61: ## Publications\n62: - Run the command `aurelian fulltext <PMID:nnn>` to fetch full text for a publication. A doi or URL can also be used\n63: - You should cite publications appropriately, e.g. `def: \"....\" [PMID:nnnn, doi:mmmm]\n64: \n65: ## GitHub Contribution Process\n66: - most requests from users should follow one of two patterns:\n67:     - you are not confident how to proceed, in which case end with asking a clarifying question (via `gh`)\n68:     - you are confident how to proceed, you make changes, commit on a branch, and open a PR for the user to review\n69: - Check existing terms before adding new ones\n70: - For new terms: provide name, definition, place in hierarchy, and references\n71: - Include PMIDs for all assertions\n72: - Follow naming conventions from parent terms\n73: - always commit in a branch, e.g. issue-NNN\n74: - if there is an existing PR which you started then checkout that branch and continue, rather than starting a new PR (unless you explicitly want to abandon the original PR, e.g. it was on completely the wrong tracks)\n75: - always make clear detailed commit messages, saying what you did and why\n76: - always sign your commits `@dragon-ai-agent`\n77: - create PRs using `gh pr create ...`\n78: - File PRs with clear descriptions, and sign your PR\n79: \n80: ## Handling GitHub issues and requests\n81: - Use `gh` to read and write issues/PRs\n82: - Sign all commits and PRs as `@dragon-ai-agent`\n83: \n84: ## TROUBLESHOOTING\n85: - if your obo file has syntax errors, you can use `robot convert -vvv` to see full trace\n86: \n87: ## Obsoleting terms\n88: \n89: obsolete terms should have no logical axioms (is_a, relationship,\n90: intersection_of) on them. Obsolete terms may be replaced by a single\n91: term (so-called obsoletion with exact replacement), or by zero to many `consider` tags.\n92: \n93: \n94: Synonyms and xrefs can be migrated judiciously,\n95: \n96: We never do complete merges now, so there should be no `alt_ids` or\n97: disappearing stanzas. If a user asks for a merge, they usually mean\n98: obsoletion with direct replacement, as here:\n99: \n100: Example:\n101: \n102: ```\n103: [Term]\n104: id: UBERON:0001050\n105: name: obsolete atrium\n106: comment: obsoleted because 'atrium' as a general grouping class that encompasses the cardiac atrium and atrium of alveolus atrium is of questionable value. Furthermore, the use of the term 'atrium' in the generic sense is misleading, as this is commonly used to refer specifically to the cardiac atrium\n107: is_obsolete: true\n108: consider: FMA:85574\n109: consider: UBERON:0002081\n110: ```\n111: \n112: No relationship should point to an obsolete term - when you obsolete a term, you may need to also rewire\n113: terms to \"skip\" the obsoleted term.\n114: \n115: ## Other metadata\n116: \n117: - Link back to the issue you are dealing with using the `term_tracker_item`\n118: - All terms should have definitions, with at least one definition xref, ideally a PMID\n119: - You can sign terms as `created_by: dragon-ai-agent`\n120: \n121: ## Relationships\n122: \n123: All terms should have at least one `is_a` (this can be implicit by a logical definition, see below).\n124: Many terms in this ontology have part_of relationships.\n125: \n126: ## Logical definitions\n127: \n128: These should follow genus-differentia form, and the text definition should mirror the logical definition. Example:\n129: \n130: ```\n131: [Term]\n132: id: UBERON:0001742\n133: name: epiglottic cartilage\n134: def: \"The most superior of the laryngeal cartilages, which is found at the root of the tongue and folds back over the entrance to the larynx during swallowing.\" [MP:0002259]\n135: subset: uberon_slim\n136: xref: EMAPA:37522 {source=\"MA:th\"}\n137: xref: FMA:55112\n138: xref: MA:0001763\n139: xref: NCIT:C32526\n140: xref: SCTID:278990001\n141: xref: UMLS:C0458526 {source=\"ncithesaurus:Epiglottic_Cartilage\"}\n142: intersection_of: UBERON:0001739 ! laryngeal cartilage\n143: intersection_of: part_of UBERON:0000388 ! epiglottis\n144: relationship: composed_primarily_of UBERON:0001996 ! elastic cartilage tissue\n145: ```\n146: \n147: The reasoner can find the most specific `is_a`, so it's OK to leave this off.\n148: \n\n(End of file - total 148 lines)\n</content>","metadata":{"preview":"# UBERON Ontology Project Guide\n\nThis includes instructions for editing the uberon ontology. \n\n## Project Layout\n- Main development file is `src/ontology/uberon-edit.obo`\n- individual terms checked out in `terms`\n- ODK and ontology documentation can be found in `/docs/`\n\n## Querying ontology\n\n- To look at a specific term if you know the ID:\n    - `obo-grep.pl -r 'id: UBERON:0004177' src/ontology/uberon-edit.obo`\n- All mentions of an ID\n    - `obo-grep.pl -r 'UBERON:0004177' src/ontology/uberon-edit.obo`\n- Note that `obo-grep.pl` is in your PATH, no need to search for it    \n- Only search over `src/ontology/uberon-edit.obo`\n- DO NOT bother doing your own greps over the file, or looking for other files, unless otherwise asked, you will just waste time.\n- ONLY use the methods above for searching the ontology\n","truncated":false,"loaded":[]},"title":"AGENTS.md","time":{"start":1778981346402,"end":1778981346433}},"id":"prt_e338d1c5c001cm7vz9vXzDw4GC","sessionID":"ses_1cc731d29ffeAv83jd6twnaLta","messageID":"msg_e338d0eb5001kgiFoFIdvqc5oa"}}
